This article first appeared at southern weekend and is not to be reprinted without permission

By Liu Shiyang and Wang Weikai, southern weekend journalists

Editor in chief | Zhang Yue

Over the past month, many ordinary people have slipped out of the world in the face of the epidemic.

As the birthplace of the epidemic, Wuhan had the highest number of deaths, with 2,104 deaths as of 12:00 on February 27,2020, accounting for 77 percent of all deaths in the country.

Wu Qian, a 37-year-old dispatcher at the Wuhan Aid Management Station, is one of them.

No one can fully outline their True Path from infection to death, but it should be remembered that in the early spring of 2020, when the Chinese fought the new coronavirus, their efforts and helplessness.

1
One last mission

1

###One last mission

At noon on January 16, Wu Qian, a dispatcher at the Wuhan Rescue and Management Station, was given the task of escorting a deaf boy who had come to Wuhan by train alone to his home.

It's part of his routine to escort people home. Wu Qian is a native of Wuhan. He was born in November 1982. He graduated from the Wuhan University of Technology Art and Design Program in 2005 and was admitted to the Wuhan Relief Administration Center in 2010. The rescue management station is under the civil administration system, which was formerly known as the shelter and repatriation station. It was renamed in 2003. Every Spring Festival is the busiest time for aid stations across the country, and homeless people are always in need of help.

According to Wu's colleague Yang Xiao, because the boy's father was already waiting in Guangzhou, the unit asked them to pack up 10 minutes after they received the assignment and rush to the Hankou Railway Station.

At that time, Wuhan had not yet entered a state of tension, and few people in the station wore masks. It was night when he returned the child to his father in Guangzhou. It was the Spring Festival travel season. Tickets for returning to Wuhan had already sold out. Wu Qian contacted the local work station and tried to arrange a 10:30 pm station ticket. A group of people crowded in the dining car, Wu Qian gave up his seat to colleagues, himself sitting on the floor of the car aisle to eat instant noodles.

Wu Qian, who has been doing relief work for ten years, did not think at this time that what he had just completed was the last task in his life.

According to Zhang Xiaolu, Wu Qian's lover, to the southern weekend reporters recalled that business trips were Wu Qian's normal work routine. The two registered for marriage in May 2010, and in June Wu Qian went to work in a rescue station. He was responsible for his work and rushed to do everything. His work started as a street patrol, but gradually it became a business escort. She knew that her husband was thrifty, worked hard, and worried that he would not be able to eat or live well alone.

In the unit, Wu Qian's work originally is the dispatch, but as long as the manpower is insufficient, other matters also must top. Over the years, they've had a lot of fights about business trips.

On the way back, Wu Qian told Zhang Xiaolu that he would not arrive in Wuhan until 3 am on the 17th and decided not to go home directly to work, sleep for a while and then go to work.

On the afternoon of January 17, Wu Qian went home from work as usual. As he had not had a good rest the day before, he chatted with his family and went to bed. When he got up the next morning, he felt very tired and his temperature was 102.

Wuhan was not yet under the shadow of the epidemic. The day Wu Qian found out that he had a fever was the lunar new year. In the Baibu Pavilion Garden Community in Jiang'an District, Wuhan, more than 40,000 families are gathering for what would become known as a "family feast" .

Because there are two daughters, the youngest is only two years old. Zhang Xiaolu is worried about the flu, afraid of infection to the child, he urged Wu Qian to go to the hospital to hang needles. The normal life of a family comes to an abrupt end at that moment.

2
"I hope the station can save me. "

2

###"I hope the station can save me. "

Wu Qian has been staying in the hotel since January 18. He wrote in a friend's circle: "Do good things and be lucky" -- the last entry on his friends' circle was a picture of him and the deaf boy's family after his business trip to Guangzhou on the 16th.

But Good Fortune did not befall Wu Qian. He continued to have a fever. On January 20, Wu's CT showed a ground-glass white shadow on his lung. The doctor told him at the time that it was viral pneumonia, but there was no definite answer as to what the virus was.

It was also the first day that the Wuhan epidemic received public attention. On the same day, Academician Zhong Nanshan confirmed for the first time that there was human to human transmission of the new coronavirus. From that day on, the National Health Commission began to compile and release new cases every day, with cases appearing in Beijing, Shanghai and other cities one after another.

In Wuhan, the crisis lurks below the surface. After the human-to-human transmission was made public, patients crowded the fever clinic in Wuhan in just a few days.

On January 20, Wu asked his immediate boss, Ge Fei, for leave of absence via wechat and explained his condition. Ge Fei asked: Is it the new coronavirus? Wu Qian replied that he could not be hospitalized, there are no beds in the suction department, and there is no nucleic acid test kit, also can not find out, can only first injection to see.

In order to do the test as early as possible, Wu Qian went to the community hospital, Xinhua Hospital, Wuhan Central Hospital and Wuhan Red Cross Hospital, but was never admitted to hospital for treatment. At home, Zhang also frantically called the community to report cases for hospitalization, only to be disappointed by the response -- as if no treatment meant no nucleic acid test, and no confirmation of the test results, the community won't be able to report back.

He's stuck in a loop. Over the next week, Wu became a "suspected patient" hovering over the statistics.

As a colleague of ten years, in the Wechat chat records of Ge Fei and Wu Qian, Wu Qian was at first quite optimistic, he did not seem to believe that he was infected with new coronary pneumonia. He had replied to Ge Fei that the doctor had advised him to get an injection at the clinic and that going to the hospital would only make it worse. "The disease has been isolated for a long time. "

In those days when Wu Qian was seeking medical treatment, all Zhang Xiaolu could do was keep calling and urging Wu Qian to change to a better hotel. During this period, Wu Qian's father had accompanied him to the hospital to line up for an examination, and the two of them waited from morning until evening. Later, Wu Qian himself went to the hotel to stay, the old man also sent him rice, every time to see him more than two eyes, but in order to isolate, Wu Qian always hide in the toilet, let his father put the rice down and go.

But on New Year's Eve, his mother really missed her son, so she went to the hotel to see him. He developed fever shortly after returning home. Zhang Xiaolu recalled that her mother-in-law should have been infected that day, but they hoped that Wu Qian had peace of mind to cure the disease at that time, and did not tell him.

The family was cut off from the disease. In the days that followed, despair and pessimism began to overshadow Wu Qian. On January 26, when chatting with GE FEI on Wechat, he said, the solution now is to stay outside until the hospital is exhausted. Ge Fei reported these situations to the station, he hoped to help him with his bed, but it was at the height of the outbreak in Wuhan, where 698 new cases had been reported on the day they spoke.

Until now, Wu had not been diagnosed with a new coronary pneumonia, and he had not received more treatment as a result. In his conversation with Ge Fei, he said for the first and only time, "I hope the station saves me. "

So on until January 28, Wu Qian finally admitted to the Hankou Hospital. But by this time his condition had entered a critical condition, and even his family could not learn about Wu's condition every day because Wuhan had initiated the most stringent quarantine measures at that time. Colleague Yang Xiao later recalled that after he was hospitalized, Wu Qian once sent out a wechat message asking about his condition. Wu Qian replied with only three words:

"I'm suffering. ".

3
"I want him back. "

3

###"I want him back. "

On February 10,26 days after a business trip to Guangzhou, Wu Qian, a rescuer from Wuhan, passed away.

Until his death, no one could confirm exactly how Wu Qian got sick. Many colleagues and family members contacted by southern weekend reporters speculated that he contracted the virus before and after his business trip to Guangzhou on January 16. But in Zhang Xiaolu's view, on January 18, Wu Qian was not given effective treatment after a fever, as well as multiple visits to the hospital may exist cross-infection, is the most important reason for his illness.

Like most ordinary Wuhan residents, who were initially kept in the dark, the patients had to rely on official accounts to determine their route of infection. In Zhang Xiaolu's memory, they do not eat seafood, also never went to the south China seafood market.

And Ge Fei told southern weekend that Wu Qian must have caught it at work. Apart from a business trip to Guangzhou, the Wuhan Rescue and Management Station has an office near the south China Seafood Market, where they used to go.

But Wu Qian is the only one who is sick in the whole rescue station. Yang Xiao, who had traveled with him to Guangzhou on business, later developed a fever, but it was only a day after taking the medicine.

An hour before Wu's death, the hospital had called Zhang Xiaolu to inform her that she might not make it. Zhang Xiaolu let the doctor help connect the video, to see him one last time.

Wu's seven-year-old daughter was nearby when the video went live. She had not seen her father for 23 days. As soon as she saw him, she burst into tears and repeatedly asked her mobile phone, "what's wrong with you, dad? Why are you lying down? "

At that time, Wu Qian was unable to speak. It was the family's last good-bye. Zhang said she had never seen her daughter cry so much.

In the impression of colleagues and family members, Wu Qian has always been an optimistic and strong man. Three days before his death, he had hoped for a miracle. On Feb. 7, he wrote on Qzone: "Every day I grind my teeth to check up on them, just for the ones behind me. I hope my inflection point will come soon. "

But the miracle didn't happen. Now, Zhang Xiaolu has rarely mentioned Wu Qian at home. During the day, she did everything she could to keep busy, taking care of her two children and the household. Until the children are asleep at night, she will open the door into Wu Qian's study, quietly miss her husband.

She cried almost the whole time when she spoke of Wu Qian. When asked by southern weekend about what Wu had said to impress you during those 24 days, she replied:

"He said he was sorry that he couldn't be at home for this period of time. I said it's OK, you have to refuel. He said I will treat you better after this period. "

The couple, who had been married for 10 years, had a long way to go. Their family just changed to a new house last year. Zhang Xiaolu's job is not stable, the family's income is not high, and usually big expenses are mainly met by Wu Qian. His leaving has made this family suddenly lose their pillar of support.

The body of Wuhan Rescuer Wu Qian was cremated on February 10. The mother, who is also ill, has not recovered and still does not know that her son has died. Because the epidemic prevention measures in Wuhan have not yet been lifted, and Wu's family can not handle the funeral.

"What I want now is for the epidemic to end and I want to get him back, " Zhang said.

Wu Qian's colleagues, are very emotional to him, a colleague in the chat with his last phone call, suddenly broke down in tears, hung up the southern weekend reporter's phone.
